[Static class fields](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Classes/Class_fields#Public_static_fields) are a stage 3 proposal, meaning they&#39;re not yet an official part of the JavaScript language. (Stage 4 is the final stage.) You can read more about the proposal [here](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-static-class-features) and the proposal process [here](https://tc39.es/process-document/).

Currently, Chrome (as of version 72) is the only browser that [supports](https://kangax.github.io/compat-table/esnext/#test-static_class_fields) static class fields.

To use this feature in other browsers you would need to use [Babel](https://babeljs.io/) with [@babel/plugin-proposal-class-properties](https://babeljs.io/docs/en/babel-plugin-proposal-class-properties) to transpile your code. If you&#39;re not already using Babel, however, this might be overkill.

Alternatively, you can assign a property to the class after initializing it. This isn&#39;t semantically identical, but works for your (and, indeed, most) use cases.

```js
class AddOrSelectAddress {
  // ...
}

AddOrSelectAddress.body = &#39;some initial value&#39;;
```

You can see this working in the below snippet.

