Your `portfolioJSON` variable is an array of objects. `src` accepts the path of a single image.

If you want to render all images in the array you should add this to your Vue instance:

```
computed: {
    imageArray: function() {
        return this.portfolioJSON.map(obj =&gt; obj.img)
    }
}
```

This code will generate an array of paths based on your `portfolioJSON` array.

Then, in your HTML, replace this:
    
    &lt;img :src=&quot;portfolioJSON&quot; class=&quot;img-fluid&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;&gt;

with this:

    &lt;img v-for=&quot;image in imageArray&quot; :src=&quot;image&quot; class=&quot;img-fluid&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;/img&gt;

That will render an `&lt;img&gt;` for every image in your `portfolioJSON` array (and you shouldn&#39;t forget to close your tags when using Vue, it might come back to bite you later).

Or you might want to use a single `&lt;img&gt;` element with `srcset` instead of `src`, in which case you should use this piece of HTML:

    &lt;img :srcset=&quot;imageArray.join(&#39;,&#39;)&quot; class=&quot;img-fluid&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;/img&gt;

Note that, in this case, you might want to provide other info in your `srcset` alongside the sources.

